# Craft & Distinctiveness Standard

Governing rule: **beauty serves the mission** — every beautiful/distinctive choice must
help the user do or feel what the product is for; if it only impresses, cut it.

Avoid AI-generated tells: default fonts untouched; canned looks (beige+serif, violet
glow gradient, black-on-white broadsheet, generic rounded-card SaaS); centered/symmetric
with no hierarchy; grid of identical shadowed cards; decoration for its own sake; filler
copy ("elevate/seamlessly/unlock"); stock-photo vibe; no signature element; rhythmless
spacing and random accents.

Produce crafted instead: one signature element; a real typeface + considered ramp;
intentional hierarchy and focal point; cohesion across illustration/icons/motion/copy;
specific human copy incl. empty/error states; details that reward attention; bespoke
over generic where it fits.

Premium = restraint + precision (exact alignment, strict spacing, one accent, smooth
motion, tactile feedback, finish, performance) — not luxury costume (gold-on-black,
forced dark mode, gratuitous gradients/glass, decorative serifs, show-off animation).

Calibrate by surface: marketing/portfolio → lean into impact; consumer app → warm
immersion serving the emotional goal; regulated/operational dashboard → precise, calm,
fast, NOT cinematic; watch → one legible glance, near-total restraint.

At the critique step, ask: does this read as crafted or AI-generated, and does every
choice serve the mission? Fix what fails before shipping.
